// @check
// @error-at 9:9 Type `D` is defined in terms of itself with no base type, so it can never have a value
// A directly self-cyclic alias `type D = D` is degenerate NONSENSE — defined
// purely in terms of itself, no base case, so nothing can ever inhabit it. It
// gets an honest message that says so (PR #189 review), NOT the old misleading
// "opaque/recursive type aliases are not yet supported" (which implied a future
// feature). The error is reported at the DECLARATION (the self-`Alias` body), so
// it flags even when `D` is never used; the alias then binds `Never`, so this
// use site resolves quietly — exactly ONE error, no duplicate at `let d: D`.
type D = D
let d: D = 0
